knowl.intro:
        {{#scenario}}
            {{#phrasing1}}

A projectile is launched from a platform that is {{y0}} {{units}} off the ground at a speed of {{v0}} {{units}} per second. Its height above the ground is given by the following equation: 

h(t) = {{model}}.

t is measured in seconds and the height, h(t), is measured in {{units}}. Answer the following questions, rounding your answers to two decimal places.
            {{/phrasing1}}

            {{#phrasing2}}

A {{material}} hangs between two {{height}} {{units}} tall posts, roughly forming a parabola. The height of the {{material}} off of the ground is given by the following equation: 

h(x) = {{model}}.

x is the distance from the the first post in {{units}} and the height, h(x), is measured in {{units}}. Answer the following questions, rounding your answers to two decimal places.
            {{/phrasing2}}

          {{#phrasing3}}

A rancher is forming an animal enclosure next to a river. They have {{perimeter}} {{units}} of fence they can use to form the enclosure. If they make the enclosure w {{units}} wide, then the area of the enclosure is 

A(w) = {{model}} square {{units}}.

Answer the following questions, rounding your answers to two decimal places.
            {{/phrasing3}}
        {{/scenario}}


{{Prompt}}

knowl.content:
            {{#scenario}}
                {{#phrasing1}}

How high is the projectile off the ground after {{x_in}} seconds?
                {{/phrasing1}}

                {{#phrasing2}}

How high is the {{material}} above the ground at a distance of {{x_in}} {{units}} away from the first post?
                {{/phrasing2}}

                {{#phrasing3}}

What is the area of the enclosure when the width is {{x_in}}?
                {{/phrasing3}}
            {{/scenario}}

            {{#scenario}}
                {{#phrasing1}}

Use the quadratic formula to determine when the projectile will be {{output}} {{units}} off the ground.
                {{/phrasing1}}

                {{#phrasing2}}

Use the quadratic formula to determine the distance away from the first post when the {{material}} will be {{output}} {{units}} off the ground again.
                {{/phrasing2}}

                {{#phrasing3}}

Use the quadratic formula to determine the widths that will make the area of the enclosure equal to {{output}} square {{units}}?
                {{/phrasing3}}
            {{/scenario}}

            {{#scenario}}
                {{#phrasing1}}

Determine the maximum height of the projectile.
                {{/phrasing1}}

                {{#phrasing2}}

Determine the lowest height of the {{material}}.
                {{/phrasing2}}

                {{#phrasing3}}

Determine the maximum area of the enclosure.
                {{/phrasing3}}
            {{/scenario}}

knowl.outtro:
        {{#scenario}}
            {{#phrasing1}}



After {{x_in}} seconds, the projectile is {{y_out}} {{units}} off of the ground.


The projectile will be {{output}} {{units}} off the ground after {{root1}} and {{root2}} seconds.


The maximum height of the projectile is {{optimum}} {{units}}, when t = {{vertex}} seconds.

            {{/phrasing1}}

            {{#phrasing2}}



When it is {{x_in}} {{units}} away from the first post, the {{material}} is {{y_out}} {{units}} off of the ground.


The {{material}} will be {{output}} {{units}} off the ground again when x = {{root1}} and x = {{root2}} {{units}}.


The lowest height of the {{material}} is {{optimum}} {{units}}, when x = {{vertex}}.

            {{/phrasing2}}

            {{#phrasing3}}

Multiplied out, the model is A(w) = {{simplified_model}}.



When the width is {{x_in}} {{units}}, the area is {{y_out}} square {{units}}.


The enclosure will have area {{output}} square {{units}} when w = {{root1}} and w = {{root2}} {{units}}.


The maximum area of the enclosure is {{optimum}} square {{units}}, when w = {{vertex}} {{units}}.

            {{/phrasing3}}
        {{/scenario}}
